Southport Regional Park
tags.note: Boundaries in GIS. Owned by the State, and leased to Osceola County for management. Totacres from October 2013 land management plan for the park.
tags.note_1: Southport is comprised of boat ramp, parking facilities, pavilions and mowed lawn areas, lake littoral zones, a concessionaire building, camp sites, and natural vegetation. The site has been used for boating access to Lake Toho, passive recreation, and c
tags.note_2: oncessionaire airboat tours for many years. A small cypress wetland and large oak hammocks.Southport provides habitat for wading and water dependent birds as well as potential habitat for gopher tortoises and species that utilize oak hammock areas.

tags.name: Twin Oaks Conservation Area
tags.note: This property contains herbaceous wetlands, upland oak forests and improved pasture in addition to more than a mile of shoreline of Lake Tohopekaliga. The wetlands on site include several man-made ditches, an excavated pond, several wet prairies and two
tags.note_1: freshwater marshes. The conceptual use plan for the property consists of hiking/equestrian trail, fishing pier, canoe/kayak launch, in addition to restoration of the wetland marsh area.

tags.name: Cherokee Point Conservation Area
tags.note: Bordered on the north by Lake Tohopekaliga, this property contains improved pasture, lake littoral zone, freshwater marsh, and an upland ridge peninsula which provide habitat for bald eagle, snail kite, limpkin, white ibis and other wading birds and wild
tags.note_1: life. The conceptual plan includes a boardwalk access for wildlife observation, a large picnic pavilion, and a canoe/kayak trail to link with Twin Oaks Conservation Area.
